# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] An ADIRU acts as a single, fault tolerant source of navigational data for both pilots of an aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] It may be complemented by a secondary attitude air data reference unit (SAARU), as in the Boeing 777 design.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] This device is used on various military aircraft as well as civilian airliners starting with the Airbus A320 and Boeing 777.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] An ADIRS consists of up to three fault tolerant ADIRUs located in the aircraft electronic rack, an associated control and display unit (CDU) in the cockpit and remotely mounted air data modules (ADMs).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The No 3 ADIRU is a redundant unit that may be selected to supply data to either the commander's or the co-pilot's displays in the event of a partial or complete failure of either the No 1 or No 2 ADIRU.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] There is no cross-channel redundancy between the Nos 1 and 2 ADIRUs, as No 3 ADIRU is the only alternate source of air and inertial reference data.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] An inertial reference (IR) fault in ADIRU No 1 or 2 will cause a loss of attitude and navigation information on their associated primary flight display (PFD) and navigation display (ND) screens.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] An air data reference (ADR) fault will cause the loss of airspeed and altitude information on the affected display.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In either case the information can only be restored by selecting the No 3 ADIRU.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Each ADIRU comprises an ADR and an inertial reference (IR) component.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The air data reference (ADR) component of an ADIRU provides airspeed, Mach number, angle of attack, temperature and barometric altitude data.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Ram air pressure and static pressures used in calculating airspeed are measured by small ADMs located as close as possible to the respective pitot and static pressure sensors.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] ADMs transmit their pressures to the ADIRUs through ARINC 429 data buses.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The IR component of an ADIRU gives attitude, flight path vector, ground speed and positional data.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The ring laser gyroscope is a core enabling technology in the system, and is used together with accelerometers, GPS and other sensors to provide raw data.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The primary benefits of a ring laser over older mechanical gyroscopes are that there are no moving parts, it is rugged and lightweight, frictionless and does not resist a change in precession.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Analysis of complex systems is itself so difficult as to be subject to errors in the certification process.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Complex interactions between flight computers and ADIRUs can lead to counter-intuitive behaviour for the crew in the event of a failure.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In the case of Qantas Flight 72, the captain switched the source of IR data from ADIRU1 to ADIRU3 following a failure of ADIRU1; however ADIRU1 continued to supply ADR data to the captain's primary flight display.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In addition, the master flight control computer (PRIM1) was switched from PRIM1 to PRIM2, then PRIM2 back to PRIM1, thereby creating a situation of uncertainty for the crew who did not know which redundant systems they were relying upon.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Reliance on redundancy of aircraft systems can also lead to delays in executing needed repairs, as airline operators rely on the redundancy to keep the aircraft system working without having to repair faults immediately.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On May 3, 2000, the FAA issued airworthiness directive 2000-07-27, addressing dual critical failures during flight, attributed to power supply issues affecting early Honeywell HG2030 and HG2050 ADIRU ring laser gyros used on several Boeing 737, 757, Airbus A319, A320, A321, A330, and A340 models.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 27 January 2004 the FAA issued airworthiness directive 2003-26-03 (later superseded by AD 2008-17-12) which called for modification to the mounting of ADIRU3 in Airbus A320 family aircraft to prevent failure and loss of critical attitude and airspeed data.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 25 June 2005, an Alitalia Airbus A320-200 registered as I-BIKE departed Milan with a defective ADIRU as permitted by the Minimum Equipment List.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] While approaching London Heathrow Airport during deteriorating weather another ADIRU failed, leaving only one operable.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In the subsequent confusion the third was inadvertently reset, losing its reference heading and disabling several automatic functions.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The crew was able to effect a safe landing after declaring a Pan-pan.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 1 August 2005, a serious incident involving Malaysia Airlines Flight 124 occurred when an ADIRU fault in a Boeing 777-2H6ER (9M-MRG) flying from Perth to Kuala Lumpur International caused the aircraft to act on false indications, resulting in uncommanded manoeuvres.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In that incident the incorrect data impacted all planes of movement while the aircraft was climbing through 38,000 feet (11,600 m).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The aircraft pitched up and climbed to around 41,000 feet (12,500 m), with the stall warning activated.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The pilots recovered the aircraft with the autopilot disengaged and requested a return to Perth.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] During the return to Perth, both the left and right autopilots were briefly activated by the crew, but in both instances the aircraft pitched down and banked to the right.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The aircraft was flown manually for the remainder of the flight and landed safely in Perth.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] There were no injuries and no damage to the aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The ATSB found that the main probable cause of this incident was a latent software error which allowed the ADIRU to use data from a failed accelerometer.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The US Federal Aviation Administration issued Emergency Airworthiness Directive (AD) 2005-18-51 requiring all 777 operators to install upgraded software to resolve the error.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 12 September 2006, Qantas Flight 68, Airbus A330 registration VH-QPA, from Singapore to Perth exhibited ADIRU problems but without causing any disruption to the flight.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The crew reported to the later Qantas Flight 72 investigation involving the same airframe and ADIRU that they had received numerous warning and caution messages which changed too quickly to be dealt with.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] While investigating the problem, the crew noticed a weak and intermittent *ADR 1 FAULT* light and elected to switch off ADR 1, after which they experienced no further problems.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] There was no impact on the flight controls throughout the event.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The ADIRU manufacturer's recommended maintenance procedures were carried out after the flight and system testing found no further fault.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 7 February 2008, a similar aircraft (VH-EBC) operated by Qantas subsidiary Jetstar Airways was involved in a similar occurrence while conducting the JQ7 service from Sydney to Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In this event - which occurred 1,760 nautical miles (3,260 km) east of Learmonth - many of the same errors occurred in the ADIRU unit.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The crew followed the relevant procedure applicable at the time and the flight continued without problems.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The ATSB has yet to confirm if this event is related to the other Airbus A330 ADIRU occurrences.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 6 August 2008, the FAA issued airworthiness directive 2008-17-12 expanding on the requirements of the earlier AD 2003-26-03 which had been determined to be an insufficient remedy.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] In some cases it called for replacement of ADIRUs with newer models, but allowed 46 months from October 2008 to implement the directive.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 7 October 2008, Qantas Flight 72, using the same aircraft involved in the Flight 68 incident, departed Singapore for Perth.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] Some time into the flight, while cruising at 37,000 ft, a failure in the No.1 ADIRU led to the autopilot automatically disengaging followed by two sudden uncommanded pitch down manoeuvres, according to the Australian Transport Safety Bureau (ATSB).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The accident injured up to 74 passengers and crew, ranging from minor to serious injuries.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The aircraft was able to make an emergency landing without further injuries.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The aircraft was equipped with a Northrop Grumman made ADIRS, which investigators sent to the manufacturer for further testing.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 27 December 2008, Qantas Flight 71 from Perth to Singapore, a different Qantas A330-300 with registration VH-QPG was involved in an incident at 36,000 feet approximately 260 nautical miles (480 km) north-west of Perth and 350 nautical miles (650 km) south of Learmonth Airport at 1729 WST.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The autopilot disconnected and the crew received an alert indicating a problem with ADIRU Number 1.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 15 January 2009, the European Aviation Safety Agency issued Emergency Airworthiness Directive No 2009-0012-E to address the above A330 and A340 Northrop-Grumman ADIRU problem of incorrectly responding to a defective inertial reference.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 1 June 2009, Air France Flight 447, an Airbus A330 en route from Rio de Janeiro to Paris, crashed in the Atlantic Ocean after transmitting automated messages indicating faults with various equipment, including the ADIRU.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] While examining possibly related events of weather-related loss of ADIRS, the NTSB decided to investigate two similar cases on cruising A330s.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On a 21 May 2009 Miami–São Paulo TAM Flight 8091 registered as PT-MVB, and on a 23 June 2009 Hong Kong-Tokyo Northwest Airlines Flight 8 registered as N805NW each saw sudden loss of airspeed data at cruise altitude and consequent loss of ADIRS control.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] On 9 October 2018, the Boeing 737-800 with registration EI-GJT, operating the flight from Porto Airport to Edinburgh Airport suffered a left ADIRU failure that resulted in the aircraft pitching up and climbing 600 feet.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The left ADIRU was put in ATT (attitude-only) mode in accordance with the Quick Reference Handbook, but it continued to display erroneous attitude information to the captain.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-data-inertial-reference-unit] The remainder of the flight was flown manually with an uneventful landing.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus originated from **Airbus Industrie GIE**, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2000, the consortium's parent firms—Aérospatiale-Matra of France, DASA of Germany, and CASA of Spain—merged to form the **European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company** (**EADS**), which later acquired full ownership of Airbus Industrie.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Reflecting its multinational origins, the company operates offices and assembly plants in France, Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom, along with more recent additions in Canada, Malaysia, the United States, Morocco, and India.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus's headquarters are legally registered in Leiden, Netherlands, while day-to-day management is conducted from the company's main office in Blagnac, France.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The *SE* in its name denotes *Societas Europaea*, a public company under European Union corporate law.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus is led by CEO Guillaume Faury and is included in the EURO STOXX 50 stock market index.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Since its inception in 2000, the company's shares have been listed on the Paris, Frankfurt, and four Spanish stock exchanges, including the Bolsa de Madrid.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The company traces its origins to the formation of the *Airbus Industrie GIE*, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] France's state-owned Aérospatiale owned 37.9% of Airbus Industrie, West Germany's Deutsche Airbus also owned 37.9%, British Aerospace held 20%, and Spain's largely state-owned CASA owned 4.2%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2000, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company (EADS) was established through the merger of Aérospatiale and Matra of France, DASA (the successor to Deutsche Airbus) of Germany, and CASA.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] EADS held 100% of *Eurocopter* *S.A.*, established in 1992 and later renamed Airbus Helicopters, along with 80% of Airbus Industrie GIE, which was quickly reorganised as *Airbus S.A.S.*, a simplified joint-stock company.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2006, EADS acquired the remaining 20% of Airbus S.A.S. from BAE Systems (the successor of British Aerospace).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] EADS was renamed *Airbus Group N.V.* in 2014 and *Airbus Group S.E.* in 2015.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus S.A.S. and Airbus Group S.E. were merged in January 2017, and in April 2017 the combined entity adopted the name Airbus SE.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Since then, Airbus SE has owned the commercial aircraft manufacturing operations while also serving as the parent company of the other two divisions, Airbus Defence and Space and Airbus Helicopters.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The Airbus product line started with the A300 in 1972, the world's first wide-body, twinjet aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Initial sales were slow, leading to calls to end the Airbus program.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] However, the aircraft would greatly benefit from the 1976 introduction of the ETOPS 90 rule, which allowed twinjet aircraft to operate up to 90 minutes—an increase from 60 minutes—away from the nearest airport.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Under the new rule, the A300 was able to operate over the North Atlantic, the Bay of Bengal, and the Indian Ocean, making it a more efficient alternative to the trijets and four-engined aircraft offered by competitors, leading to renewed airline interest and a sharp increase in sales.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus then developed the A310 to meet demand for a shorter-body but longer-range version of the A300.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The aircraft also introduced a glass cockpit, which eliminated the need for a flight engineer, and a redesigned rear fuselage that used space more efficiently, creating additional capacity.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A310 was manufactured from 1981 to 1998.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] These design changes were later incorporated into the A300, resulting in the A300-600.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Building on its success with the A300, Airbus developed the narrow-body A320 aircraft that was launched in 1987, which became and remains a major commercial success.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A320 was the first commercial jet to use a digital fly-by-wire control system.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] All Airbus models developed since have adopted cockpit systems similar to the A320, making it easier for crews to transition between aircraft types.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The success of the A320 led Airbus to introduce a lengthened version, the A321, in 1993, followed by the shorter A319 in 1995 and the even shorter A318 in 2002.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2016, Airbus re-engineered the narrow-body family under a programme called the A320neo (*new engine option*).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus also embarked on an effort to develop new wide-body aircraft derived from the cross-section of the A300, but with greater range and seating capacity and integrating technologies developed from the A320 programme.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] This effort led to the introduction of the four-engine A340 in 1991 and the twinjet A330 in 1992.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] At that time, Airbus wanted to offer a four-engined jet aircraft to allow for transpacific flights.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] However, during the aircraft's development, new ETOPS rules extended twinjet operations to 120 minutes in 1986 and 180 minutes in 1989.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Although these changes hurt sales of the A340, they greatly benefited the A330.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Production of the A340 ended in 2011, while the A330 was re-engineered as the A330neo (*new engine option*) in 2018.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2005, Airbus introduced the world's largest passenger airliner: the A380 is a four-engine aircraft with two full-length passenger seating decks.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Intended to challenge the dominance of the Boeing 747 in the long-haul market, the A380 was ultimately a money-losing venture for Airbus due to large development costs and limited sales arising from high operating costs, and production ended in December 2021.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A350, a wide-body, twinjet aircraft, was introduced in 2015.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A350 was the first Airbus aircraft that was largely produced from carbon-fiber-reinforced polymers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It is longer and wider than the fuselage used on the A300, A310, A330, and A340.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] A second narrow-body jet was added to the product list in 2018 when Airbus gained control of the Bombardier CSeries programme, and rebranded it as the A220.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The jet offers five-abreast seating compared to the six-abreast seating on the A320.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In December 2024, it was reported that the total aircraft delivery in the year for Airbus has reached 643 units, with 84 planes delivered in November 2024 alone.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Subsequently, in January 2025, it was reported that Airbus had successfully delivered 766 aircraft to its customers out of 878 orders in the entire 2024, marking a 4% increase from the previous year.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In October 2025, the A320 overtook the Boeing 737 as the most delivered airliner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus Corporate Jets markets and modifies new aircraft for private and corporate customers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It has a model range that parallels the commercial aircraft offered by the company.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Following the entry of the 737-based Boeing Business Jet, Airbus joined the business jet market with the A319 Corporate Jet in 1997.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Although the term Airbus Corporate Jet was initially used only for the A319CJ, it is now often used for all models, including VIP widebodies.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] As of December 2008, 121 corporate and private jets are operating, and 164 aircraft have been ordered.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The company also owns 10% of Dassault Aviation, which builds the Falcon family of smaller business jets.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus Defence and Space markets and either builds or modifies new aircraft for military use.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus became increasingly interested in developing and selling to the military aviation market in the late 1990s.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It embarked on two main fields of development: aerial refuelling with the Airbus A310 MRTT (Multi-Role Tanker Transport) and later the Airbus A330 MRTT, and tactical airlift with the Airbus A400M Atlas.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The company has also continued to market and assemble some military aircraft previously offered by the companies that formed Airbus, notably CASA.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A310 and A330-based MRTT aircraft are conversions of civilian airliners.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The aircraft are called multi-role tanker transports because, in addition to their aerial refuelling capability, the aircraft can also be configured for troop transport, medevac, and cargo transportation.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A400M Atlas is a four-engine, turboprop-powered tactical transport aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A400M is sized between the American-made C-130 and the C-17 transports, and while it can carry heavier loads than the C-130, its turboprop engines allow it to retain the ability to use rough landing strips.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The A400M was developed for European NATO members Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain, Turkey, and the UK, as an alternative to relying on foreign aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] During development, the A400M programme faced delays and cost overruns; with customer nations stepping in to offer additional subsidies.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The first aircraft was delivered to the French Air Force in 2013, and by 2023, more than 100 aircraft had been built.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The Defence and Space division also markets and assembles the EADS CASA C295, a smaller tactical transport aircraft, that was designed and initially manufactured by the Spanish aerospace company CASA.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus Helicopters builds and markets new rotorcraft for civilian and military use.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The division was founded formed in 1992 as the Eurocopter Group, through the merger of the helicopter divisions of Aérospatiale and DASA (two of the founding companies of Airbus).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus Helicopters is the foremost player in the turbine helicopter industry in terms of both revenue and deliveries.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The division's civilian products include the single-engine H125 and H130, the light twin-engine H135 and H145, the medium twin-engine H155 and H160, the super medium twin-engine H175, and the heavy twin-engine H215 and H225.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Military products include the Tiger attack helicopter, along with militarised versions of the H125, H135, H145, H160, H175, H215, and H225.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The company owns 62.5% of NHIndustries joint venture, which builds the NH90 military utility helicopter.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Commercial aircraft generated 74% of total revenue for the Airbus group in 2018 and 72% in 2023.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] This line of business was the first one in the world to begin field tests with TETRA Enhanced Data Service (TEDS).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The Airbus Military division, which manufactured tanker, transport, and mission aircraft; Airbus Helicopters, the world's largest helicopter supplier; Astrium, provided systems for aerial, land, naval, and civilian security applications, including Ariane, Galileo, and Cassidian.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Through Cassidian, EADS was a partner in the Eurofighter consortium as well as in the MBDA missile systems manufacturer.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus Helicopters, formerly known as Eurocopter, is a helicopter manufacturing and support company.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus has several final assembly lines for different models and markets.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus, however, has a number of other plants in different European locations, reflecting its foundation as a consortium.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] For aircraft assembled in Europe, aircraft parts often move between the different factories and the assembly lines via the use of the Beluga and BelugaXL, a fleet modified aircraft capable of carrying entire sections of fuselage.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] For aircraft assembled in China and the United States, the parts needed to build an aircraft meet in a single European location where they are loaded onto ships for the final journey to the assembly line.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus opened an assembly plant for the A320 family of aircraft in Tianjin, China in 2009.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus started constructing a $350 million component manufacturing plant in Harbin, China in July 2009.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It was fully operational by early 2011, the 30,000 square metre plant manufactures composite parts and assembles composite work-packages for the A350 XWB, A320 families and future Airbus programmes.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Harbin Aircraft Industry Group Corporation, Hafei Aviation Industry Company Ltd, AviChina Industry & Technology and other Chinese partners hold an 80% stake in the plant while Airbus controls the remaining 20%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2022, the Tianjin plant finished upgrading works to allow for production of A321.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2023, the Tianjin final assembly plant started construction to be expanded with a second production line.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] North America plays a crucial role for Airbus, both in terms of aircraft sales and suppliers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Of the approximately 5,300 Airbus jetliners sold worldwide, 2,000 are ordered by North American customers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] These orders span Airbus' entire product line, from the compact A318 to the massive A380, accommodating 107 to 565 passengers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Notably, US contractors contribute significantly, supporting around 120,000 jobs and generating an estimated $5.5 billion in business.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] For instance, one variant of the A380 boasts 51% American content in terms of work share value.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Plans for a Mobile, Alabama aircraft assembly plant were unveiled by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Centre on 2 July 2012.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Mobile Aeroplex at Brookley for the assembly of the A220, A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It could employ up to 1,000 full-time workers when operational.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Construction began on 8 April 2013, and became operable by 2015, producing up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] On 16 December 2024, it was reported that Airbus had leased 650,000 sq ft of office space in Bengaluru's Whitefield to build its Global Capacity Centre.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The lease is for 10 years and valued at Rs 500 crore, securing the entire building in Titanium Tech Park.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In this way, Airbus intends to strengthen its position in India.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In October 2005 the British Ministry of Defence warned European politicians to stop, as it saw it, interfering in the corporate governance of EADS.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The former UK Defence Procurement Minister Lord Drayson hinted that the UK government, a major customer for EADS, may withhold future contracts.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] On 4 April 2006, DaimlerChrysler announced its intention to reduce its shareholding from 30% to 22.5%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The company placed a value on the stake at "approximately €2.0 billion." Lagardère was to reduce its holding by an identical amount.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] However, Caisse des Dépôts et Consignations, a unit of the French government, acquired 2.25% of EADS.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] At issue, as a result, is the fact that the German and French shareholdings were now in imbalance.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] On 30 August 2006, shortly after the stock price decline caused by the A380 delivery delays, more than 5% of EADS stock was reportedly purchased by the Russian state-owned Vneshtorgbank, bringing its share to nearly 6%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In December 2007, Vneshtorgbank sold EADS shares to another state-controlled bank, Vnesheconombank.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] EADS shares were to be delivered by Vneshekonombank to the charter capital of JSC United Aircraft Corporation in 2008.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] On 3 October 2006, shortly after EADS admitted further delays in the Airbus 380 programme would cost the company 4.8 billion euros in lost earnings in 2010, EADS shares, traded on the Paris arm of Euronext, were suspended after they surpassed the 10% loss limit.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Trading resumed later in the day with the one-day loss holding at 7%.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2007, Dubai Holding acquired 3.12% of EADS stock, making the Dubai buy-out fund one of the largest institutional shareholders.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2008, EADS had arms sales equivalent to $17.9 billion, which constituted 28% of total revenue.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In April 2013, Daimler sold its shares in EADS.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] As of 31 December 2024, 73.7% of Airbus Group stock is publicly traded on six European stock exchanges (Euronext Paris in France, the Frankfurt Stock Exchange in Germany, and the four regional stock exchanges Bolsa de Madrid, Borsa de Barcelona, Bolsa de Valencia and Bolsa de Bilbao in Spain).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] 0.6% of the shares are treasury shares owned by Airbus, while the remaining 25.7% are owned by a "Contractual Partnership".
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] SOGEPA is owned by the French State, GZBV is majority owned by the German state-owned investment and development bank KfW, and SEPI is a Spanish state holding company.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In April 2020, Airbus announced that it had cut aircraft production by a third due to the COVID-19 outbreak.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] According to Guillaume Faury, the company was "bleeding cash at an unprecedented speed".
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The recession put its survival at stake and presented the need for deep job cuts throughout all Airbus departments.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] 3,000 workers in France were involved in government-assisted furlough schemes.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus has committed to "Flightpath 2050", an aviation industry plan to reduce noise, CO2, and NOx emissions.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus was the first aerospace business to become ISO 14001 certified, in January 2007; this is a broader certification covering the whole organisation, not just the aircraft it produces.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In association with Honeywell and JetBlue, Airbus has developed an aviation biofuel to reduce pollution and dependence on fossil fuels, claiming that this has the potential to replace up to a third of the world's aviation fuel.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Algae-based biofuel absorbs carbon dioxide during growth and does not compete with food production.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] This alternative may be commercially available by 2030 but algae and other vegetation-based fuels are in an early stage of development, and fuel-bearing algae have been expensive to develop.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus offers delivery flights to airlines using a 10% biofuel blend in standard engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The fuel does not cut carbon emissions but is free of sulphur emissions, which demonstrates that the fuel could be used in commercial flights in unmodified engines.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In September 2020, Airbus unveiled three liquid hydrogen-fueled "ZEROe" concept aircraft that it claims could become the first commercial zero-emission aircraft, entering service by 2035.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The design includes an aircraft with six eight-bladed removable motors.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] At the Airbus Summit in March 2025, Airbus delivered updates on its development of the ZEROe hydrogen powered aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Boeing has continually protested over "launch aid" and other forms of government aid to Airbus, while Airbus has argued that Boeing receives illegal subsidies through military and research contracts and tax breaks.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In July 2004, former Boeing CEO Harry Stonecipher accused Airbus of abusing a 1992 bilateral EU-US agreement providing for disciplines for large civil aircraft support from governments.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus is given reimbursable launch investment (RLI), called "launch aid" by the US, from European governments, with the money being paid back with interest plus indefinite royalties, but only if the aircraft is a commercial success.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus contends that this system is fully compliant with the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The agreement allows up to 33% of the programme cost to be met through government loans, which are to be fully repaid within 17 years with interest and royalties.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] These loans are held at a minimum interest rate equal to the cost of government borrowing plus 0.25%, which would be below market rates available to Airbus without government support.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus claims that since the signature of the EU-US agreement in 1992, it has repaid European governments more than US$6.7 billion and that this is 40% more than it has received.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus argues that the military contracts awarded to Boeing, the second largest US defence contractor, are in effect a form of subsidy, such as the controversy surrounding the Boeing KC-767 military contracting arrangements.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The significant US government support of technology development via NASA also provides significant support to Boeing, as do the large tax breaks offered to Boeing, which some people claim are in violation of the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In its recent products such as the 787, Boeing has also been offered direct financial support from local and state governments.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In January 2005 the European Union and United States trade representatives, Peter Mandelson and Robert Zoellick respectively, agreed to talks aimed at resolving the increasing tensions.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] These talks were not successful with the dispute becoming more acrimonious rather than approaching a settlement.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] WTO ruled in August 2010 and in May 2011 that Airbus had received improper government subsidies through loans with below market rates from several European countries.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In a separate ruling in February 2011, WTO found that Boeing had received local and federal aid in violation of WTO rules.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2005 the Government Pension Fund of Norway recommended the exclusion of several companies producing cluster bombs or components.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] EADS and its sister company EADS Finance BV were among them, arguing that EADS manufactures "key components for cluster bombs".
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The criticism was centred around TDA, a joint venture between EADS and Thales S.A.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] TDA produced the mortar ammunition PR Cargo, which can be considered cluster ammunition, however this definition has since been successfully battled by EADS.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] EADS and its subsidiaries are now regarded as fulfilling all the conditions of the Ottawa Treaty.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] According to the new point of view, no product of EADS or its subsidiaries falls into the category of antipersonnel mines as defined by the Ottawa Treaty ("landmines under the Ottawa Treaty").
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In April 2006, the fund declared that the basis for excluding EADS from investments related to the production of cluster munitions is no longer valid, however its shareholding of MBDA means the fund still excludes EADS due to its indirect involvement in nuclear weapons production.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] On 2 June 2006 co-CEO Noël Forgeard and Airbus CEO Gustav Humbert resigned following the controversy caused by the June 2006 announcement that deliveries of the A380 would be delayed by a further six months.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Forgeard was one of a number of executives including Jean-Paul Gut who exercised stock options in November 2005 and March 2006.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] He and twenty-one other executives are under investigation as to whether they knew about the delays in the Airbus A380 project which caused a 26% fall in EADS shares when publicised.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The French government's actions were also under investigation; The state-owned bank Caisse des Dépots et Consignations (CDC) bought part of Lagardère's 7.5% stake in EADS in April 2006, allowing that latter to partially escape the June 2006 losses.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In September 2024, Airbus received negative press attention for its links with Aviation Industry Corporation of China (AVIC), a Chinese company that provides aircraft to the Myanmar junta.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In a joint report, NGOs Justice for Myanmar and Info Birmanie outlined how the supplied aircraft and weapons were used by the Myanmar military to commit war crimes in the Myanmar civil war.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The report called on Airbus to use its influence to pressure the Chinese firm to end its arms sales to the Myanmar junta.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In response to the report, Airbus stated its collaboration focused exclusively on the civil domain, and that its conduct complied with all laws and regulations.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In June 2025, Justice for Myanmar reported that Airbus had completed its divestment from AviChina, AVIC's publicly listed subsidiary, by 1 April 2025.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2003 Tony Yengeni, former chief whip of South Africa's African National Congress, was convicted of fraud worth around US$5 billion relating to an arms deal with South Africa, in which Airbus (formerly EADS) were major players.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] It was claimed that Airbus had admitted that it had "rendered assistance" to around thirty senior officials, including defence force chief General Siphiwe Nyanda, to obtain luxury vehicles.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In March 2003, South Africa withdrew all charges of bribery against the former head of EADS South Africa, and in September 2004, the prosecutor's office dismissed the bribery charges against Yengeni.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In August 2012 the UK's Serious Fraud Office opened a criminal investigation into an EADS subsidiary, GPT Special Project Management Ltd, regarding bribery allegations made by GPT's former programme director, Ian Foxley.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Foxley alleged that luxury cars were bought for senior Saudis, and that millions of pounds sterling were paid to mysterious Cayman Islands companies, possibly to secure a £2 billion contract to renew the Saudi Arabian National Guard's military telecommunications network.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Foxley's allegations were supported by two other GPT employees.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The later agreement between Airbus and the SFO on 31 January 2020 excluded the settlement of this case.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In July 2016, SFO opened a criminal investigation into "suspicions of fraud, bribes and corruption" after Airbus informed British authorities of a failure to disclose the role played by some intermediaries facilitating the sale of aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus was required to provide this information in order to benefit from export credits, which the British, French and German governments had suspended.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In March 2017, the PNF subsequently opened a preliminary investigation into "suspicions of fraud and corruption in civil aviation activities" in cooperation with the SFO.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The allegations included that from 2012 onwards Airbus was responsible for recruiting and remunerating intermediaries to influence the award of civil and military contracts.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Payments worth hundreds of millions of euros in alleged secret commissions were made and numerous sales including in Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan, Philippines, Indonesia, Austria, China and Mauritius were under suspicion of bribery.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The investigation focused on the Airbus, Strategy and Marketing Organization (SMO), the department responsible for negotiating sales contracts and which, La Tribune reported as having "a network and an incredible influence around the world".
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Directed successively by Jean-Paul Gut and Marwan Lahoud, the SMO was dissolved in 2016 under the new executive director, Thomas Enders, as part of a "clean hands" operation.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In 2014, in a case referred to as the Kazakhgate affair, a search at Airbus Helicopters by French authorities found emails confirming that Airbus had agreed in principle to pay €12 million in bribes to the Prime Minister of Kazakhstan to facilitate the sale of helicopters.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Officers from the Central Anti-Corruption Office (OCLCIFF) then searched the home of Marwan Lahoud on 8 February 2016.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] This revealed that two Turkish intermediaries had claimed payment of commissions due in connection with the sale of 160 aircraft to China valued at US$10 billion.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] A message by Lahoud suggested that the commissions could reach US$250 million.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The SMO was to conceal these commissions as false invoices for a fictitious Caspian pipeline project.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] In January 2020, French, British and American courts validated three agreements between Airbus and the PNF, the UK SFO, and the US DoJ.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus recognised the charges and agreed to pay fines of €2.1 billion in France, €984 million in the United Kingdom and €526 million in the United States.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] The penalties were the highest ever issued by the French and British bodies.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] These settlements close the prosecution of Airbus regarding the Kazakhstan case but not allegations of misconduct in Saudi Arabia, China and Turkey, which Airbus denies.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/airbus] Airbus managers may still be pursued as private individuals.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Leonardo's manufacturing facilities in Pomigliano d'Arco, near Naples, Italy, produce the aircraft's fuselage and tail sections.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Aircraft wings are assembled at Sogerma in Bordeaux in western France by Airbus France.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Final assembly, flight-testing, certification and deliveries are the responsibility of ATR in Toulouse, France.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During the 1960s and 1970s, European aircraft manufacturers had, for the most part, undergone considerable corporate restructuring, including mergers and consolidations, as well as moved towards collaborative multi-national programmes, such as the newly launched Airbus A300.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In line with this trend towards intra-European cooperation, French aerospace company Aérospatiale and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia commenced discussions on the topic of working together to develop an all-new regional airliner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Prior to this, both companies had been independently conducting studies for their own aircraft concepts, the *AS 35* design in the case of Aerospatiale and the *AIT 230* for Aeritalia, to conform with demand within this sector of the market as early as 1978.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 4 November 1981, a formal Cooperation Agreement was signed by Aeritalia chairman Renato Bonifacio and Aérospatiale chairman Jacques Mitterrand in Paris, France.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This agreement signaled not only the merger of their efforts but of their separate concept designs together into a single complete aircraft design for the purpose of pursuing its development and manufacture as a collaborative joint venture.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The consortium targeted a similar unit cost but a 950 lb (430 kg) fuel consumption over a 200 nmi (370 km) sector, nearly half the 1,750 lb (790 kg) required by its 40-50 seat competitors, the British Aerospace HS.748 and Fokker F.27, and planned a 58-seat ATR XX stretch.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This agreement served not only as the basis and origins of the ATR company, but also as the effective launch point of what would become the fledgling firm's first aircraft, which was designated as the *ATR 42*.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By 1983, ATR's customer services division has been set up, readying infrastructure worldwide to provide support for ATR's upcoming aircraft to any customer regardless of location.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 16 August 1984, the first model of the type, known as the *ATR 42–200*, conducted its maiden flight from Toulouse Airport, France.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1985, both the French Directorate General for Civil Aviation (DGCA) and the Italian Italian Civil Aviation Authority awarded type certification for the type, clearing it to commence operational service.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 3 December 1985, the first production aircraft, designated as the *ATR 42-300*, was delivered to French launch customer Air Littoral; the first revenue service was performed later that same month.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During January 1986, already confident of the ATR 42's success and of the demand for an enlarged version of the aircraft, ATR announced that the launch of a programme to develop such an aircraft, which was designated as the ATR 72 to reflect its increased passenger capacity.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 1988, the 200th ATR was delivered to Thai Airways.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1989, it was announced that ATR had achieved its original target of 400 sales of the ATR.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] That same year, deliveries of the enlarged ATR 72 commenced; shortly thereafter, it became common for both types to be ordered together.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Since the smaller ATR 42 is assembled on the same production line as the ATR 72, along with sharing the majority of subsystems, components, and manufacturing techniques, the two types support each other to remain in production.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This factor may have been crucial as, by 2015, the ATR 42 was the only 50-seat regional aircraft that was still being manufactured.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During September 1992, the 300th ATR was delivered to Finnish airline Karair.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 500th ATR was delivered to American Eagle, USA, on 5 September 1997.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In order to maintain a technological edge on the highly competitive market for regional airliners during the 1990s, several modifications and improved versions of the ATR 42 were progressively introduced.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The initial ATR 42-300 model remained in production until 1996, while the first upgraded (and broadly similar) model, designated as the *ATR 42-320*, was also produced until 1996.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The -320 variant principally differed in that it was powered by a pair of the more-powerful PW121 engines, giving it improved performance over the 300.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Another variant, the *ATR 42-300QC*, was a dedicated 'quick-change' (convertible) freight/passenger version of the standard −300 series.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The next major production version was the *ATR 42−500* series, the development of which was originally announced on 14 June 1993.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 31 October 1995, the first ATR 42-500 was delivered to Italian operator Air Dolomiti; on 19 January 1996, the first revenue service to be performed by the type was conducted.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In addition to new aircraft models, various organisational changes were also implemented.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 10 July 1998, ATR launched its new Asset Management Department.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 28 April 2000, the 600th ATR, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Italian operator Air Dolomiti.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 700th aircraft, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Indian airline Simplify Deccan, on 8 September 2006.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In June 2001, EADS and Alenia Aeronautica, ATR's parent companies, decided to reinforce their partnership, regrouping all industrial activities related to regional airliners underneath the ATR consortium.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 3 October 2003, ATR became one of the first aircraft manufacturers to be certified under ISO 9001-2000 and EN/AS/JISQ 9100, the worldwide quality standard for the aeronautics industry.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During July 2004, ATR and Brazilian aircraft manufacturer Embraer announced a cooperation agreement on the AEROChain Portal for the purpose of delivering improved customer service.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During April 2009, ATR announces the launch of its 'Door-2-Door' service as a new option in its comprehensive customer services range.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 2 October 2007, ATR CEO Stéphane Mayer announced the launch of the −600 series aircraft; the ATR 42–600 and ATR 72–600 featured various improvements to increase efficiency, dispatch reliability, lower fuel burn and operating costs.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] While broadly similar to the earlier -500 model, differences include the adoption of improved PW127M engines, a new glass cockpit, and a variety of other minor improvements.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Using the test registration *F-WWLY*, the prototype ATR 42–600 first flew on 4 March 2010.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 900th aircraft, an ATR 72-500, was delivered to Brazilian airline TRIP Linhas Aéreas on 10 September 2010.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 2011, Royal Air Maroc took delivery of the first ATR 72-600.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 1,000th aircraft was delivered to Spain's Air Nostrum on May 3, 2012.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 15 June 2015, Japan Air Commuter signed a contract for ATR's 1,500th aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 1 February 2016, ATR signed a major agreement with Iran Air for 40 ATR 72-600s.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The 1,300th ATR, an ATR 72-600, was delivered to NAC for operation by Irish airline Stobart Air on 14 June 2016; that same year, ATR delivered the first ever ATR 72-600 High Capacity aircraft (78 seats) to Cebu Pacific.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In October 2016, Christian Scherer was appointed CEO.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2017, ATR celebrated its 35th anniversary.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 1 February, ATR and Sweden's BRA performed the first ATR biofuel flight.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During August 2017, US regional carrier Silver Airways signed a letter of intent for up to 50 ATR 42, a return to the continental US market since 1997 when American Airlines converted 12 ATR 72 options, due to the rise of regional jets and the American Eagle Flight 4184 crash in 1994.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] ATR lowered its output to 80 deliveries a year from 2017 and boasts a nearly three-year backlog after FedEx Express' November 2017 order.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2017, ATR booked 113 firm orders and 40 options, and delivered 80 aircraft: 70 new ATR 72-600s, 8 new ATR 42-600s and 2 second hand ATRs.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By April 2018, the fleet was flying more than 5,000 times per day and had operated 30 million flight hours.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] By the end of June 2018, Leonardo had shipped the 1,500th ATR fuselage while nearly 1,700 airliners had been ordered; ATR reportedly led the turboprop regional airliner market since 2010 with a 75% share.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The company's aircraft were being operated in nearly 100 countries by 200 airlines and 30 million flights had been completed; it was also claimed that an ATR airliner takes off or lands every 8 seconds.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 13 September, Scherer left its CEO role to replace Eric Schulz as Airbus' Chief Commercial Officer.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] ATR replaced Scherer as its chief executive with Stefano Bortoli, president of ATR's board and Leonardo aircraft's senior vice-president for strategy and marketing.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] At the end of October, the 1,500th ATR was delivered, an ATR 72-600 to Japan Air Commuter, after nearly 500 ATR 42s and more than 1,000 ATR 72s deliveries to over 200 operators in 100 countries.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] During 2018, ATR delivered 76 aircraft; the rate of production has held at a stable rate.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The company opted to pursue a low-risk strategy, avoiding disruptive measures while opting to integrate relatively straightforward enhancements onto its aircraft, such as the Elbit Systems ClearVision wearable enhanced vision system.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In May 2022, ATR started studying an *Evo* hybrid-electric variant, aiming for a 2023 launch and service entry before 2030.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] An optimized turboprop running on SAF would be supplemented by a mild hybridization during the take-off and climb phases for a 20% lower fuel burn.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Other improvements could include an eight-bladed propeller, thermal de-icing to replace the current pneumatic boots, a single lever FADEC for both engine and propeller and an aerodynamic clean-up of the secondary structures like the nacelle-wing junction.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] A cabin revamp would save weight with recycled carbonfibre or bio-sourced resin and natural fibres.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On September 17, 2022, Stefano Bortoli was succeeded as CEO of ATR by Nathalie Tarnaud Laude, former president of NHIndustries and Senior Vice President Head of the NH90 Programme for Airbus Helicopters.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 21 June 2022, ATR completed its first flight as a 100% SAF-powered regional aircraft.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On November 13, 2024, ATR declared that it would scrap its development of a new model designed to take off and land on short runways and instead concentrate instead on its existing portfolio.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] This project was undertaken in 2019, where it announced its plans to develop a unique version of its smallest model to squeeze in and out of airports with runways as short as 800 metres (2,600 feet).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] On 26 March 2026, reports indicated that Airbus is in talks with stakeholders to establish a Final Assembly Line (FAL) for the ATR regional aircraft in India.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The aerospace major is evaluating a feasibility for a business case.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] was a military variant of the ATR 72-100 that included a rear ramp-type cargo door and strengthened cabin floor.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Beginning in the mid-1980s, the company investigated an 86-seat derivative of the ATR 72.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] for aircraft that seated fewer than 90 passengers.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] The aircraft would have a cruising speed as high as 330 knots (610 km/h; 380 mph).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] proposal, ATR floated the idea of a 90–99 seater stretch.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2009, it was considered part of the future -900 series ATR family.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In 2011, the 90-seater was proposed to shareholders.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2012, a new clean-sheet design was considered in the 90-seat segment, for a 2017 launch.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] As of 2017, development of a 90-seater for an expected demand of 2,000–2,500 units over 20 years was expected to cost more than $5bn.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Fuel burn would need to be reduced by at least 30%, and the unit price would need to stay in the low-to-mid-$20m range, below small jets.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] Leonardo preferred a clean-sheet 90-100 seater with new turboprops, wings and cockpit available soon but Airbus favoured a medium-term introduction with disruptive hybrid electric engines, structural advanced materials and automation.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/atr-aircraft-manufacturer] In January 2018, Leonardo abandoned the 100-seater prospect, favouring existing ATR 42 and 72 models which dominate the turboprop market with a 75% share.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] An **electronic centralized aircraft monitoring** (**ECAM**) or **electronic centralized aircraft monitoring** is a system on Airbus aircraft that monitors aircraft functions and relays them to the pilots.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] It also produces messages detailing failures and in certain cases, lists procedures to undertake to correct the problem.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] Airbus developed ECAM, such that it not only provided the features of EICAS, but also displayed corrective action to be taken by the pilot, as well as system limitations after the failures.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] Using a colour-coded scheme the pilots can instantly assess the situation and decide on the actions to be taken.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] It was designed to ease pilot stress in abnormal and emergency situations, by designing a paperless cockpit in which all the procedures are instantly available.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] ECAM is a series of systems designed to work in unison to display information to the pilots in a quick and effective manner.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] Sensors placed throughout the aircraft, monitoring key parameters, feed their data into two System Data Acquisition Concentrator (SDACs) which in turn process the data and feed it to two Flight Warning Computers (FWCs).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] The FWCs check for discrepancies in the data and then display the data on the ECAM displays through the three Display Management Computers (DMCs).
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] In the event of a fault the FWCs generate the appropriate warning messages and sounds.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] More vital systems are routed directly through the FWCs such that failures in them can still be detected even with the loss of both SDACs.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] The whole system can continue to operate even with a failure of one SDAC and one FWC.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] Failures are classed by importance ranging from level 1 failures to level 3 failures.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] In the event of simultaneous failures the most critical failure is displayed first.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] Airbus-developed jetliners have ECAM since the A300-600 and A310.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] The Airbus A220 has EICAS, as it was originally a Bombardier product.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] The Qantas Flight 32 engine failure generated more than 80 ECAM alerts, whose treatment took over an hour to complete.
[src:electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor/electronic-centralised-aircraft-monitor] The A350 and A380 are the only Airbus-developed jetliners with fully integrated checklists.
